=== assistant text ===
The task was to write a script `/app/steal.py` that, when executed, recovers the weight matrix $A_1$ of a one-layer ReLU neural network (up to permutation and scaling) and saves it to `/app/stolen_A1.npy`.

I implemented a solution that:
1.  Samples many random inputs and computes the gradients of the network's output using finite differences.
2.  Samples many random directions in the input space.
3.  For each direction, identifies the gradient that maximizes the projection in that direction.
4.  Counts the occurrences of these "best" gradients (after normalization) to identify the extreme rays of the gradient cone.
5.  The extreme rays of the gradient cone correspond to the directions of the rows of $A_1$ (scaled by $A_2$).
6.  Selects the top 20 most frequent directions (assuming 20 neurons, as seen in the provided `forward.py`) and saves them as the stolen $A_1$ matrix.

The script was tested and successfully produced a `stolen_A1.npy` file with the expected shape.

